The paper focuses on the structural sparsity and bounded expansion of complex networks, which are topics related to graph theory and network analysis. Therefore, cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the analysis of network models and empirical measurements on real-world networks, which are related to statistical inference and machine learning, suggesting cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.LG (Machine Learning) as likely sub-categories. Additionally, the paper mentions the stochastic block model, which is a common model in community detection, indicating cs.SD (Sound and Music Computing) as another possible sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the perturbation of bounded-degree graphs, which is related to network resilience and security, suggesting cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) as a potential sub-category.
